Woodall’s after school program starts today!!!!

Please return the after school program paperwork ASAP. They will be coming home with students today.

If you have any questions, please call me at 918-456-1581 x4 or kkocsis@woodall.k12.ok.us

Thank you!!

INFORMATION CONCERNING OUR AFTERSCHOOL PROGRAM:

NO AFTERSCHOOL PROGRAM ON AUG 20-21

Our BGCA afterschool program will start on Monday, August 24th. It runs from 3:15 until 5:30. The program costs $20 a month per child unless you have 3 children or more and then it’s $15 per child a month. A snack will be provided, homework help and enrichment activities during Power Hour and game time for the last 30 mins. The application will be online soon on your Parent Portal account. I’ll update everyone when it’s ready. If you have any questions, you can call me at school or email me at kkocsis@woodall.k12.ok.us Thank you!!

Woodall has decided to delay the start of school for students until Thursday, August 20, 2020. This will allow more time for our staff to prepare for the very different, upcoming school year. We need to prepare technology and schedule an orientation time, for students who choose to start the year in distance learning.

School staff will still report on August 10, 2020, for professional development and preparation for the school year.

We will provide an updated school calendar after our School Board Meeting on Aug. 10th. Thank you for your patience and understanding.

post_text: Woodall Return To Learn Plan will be posted on Tuesday. I want to thank our Woodall Families for your patience! We have worked on the plan all summer, with our students and staff safety, as our first priority. Our School Board approved the plan at the July 13th meeting. We wanted to wait on finalizing the plan, until after a Cherokee County administrator meeting and the Ok State School Board meeting. Our Woodall staff is currently reviewing the plan. I will take revisions back to our School Board on Monday. Watch for our plan to be posted Tuesday on our website and Facebook page. Thank you all for your support. We are excited to start school and see our kids!

post_text: This is great news for our school and for many of our students and families. Thank you Cherokee Nation!
shared_text:
Cherokee Nation
July 2 at 6:03 PM ·

The COVID-19 pandemic has hit schools and students hard in a lot of ways. The very nature of education, how it is safely delivered in the midst of the biggest public health crisis in generations, has changed dramatically. That’s why Cherokee Nation Principal Chief Chuck Hoskin Jr. is announcing the $40 million Respond, Recover and Rebuild Education Initiative to help students and schools stay on track as we continue to deal with COVID-19.

In this video, Chief Hoskin outlines what the initiative will do:

DEADLINE EXTENDED until Sunday. If you qualify, please sign-up ASAP for free meals for your children.

If your Woodall family qualifies for free/reduced lunch, you need to signup for Meals-To-You. Every other week, you will get a free box of 10 breakfasts and 10 lunches delivered to your house for each child ages 1-18 in your household. You will receive 2 shipments in the month of June! You must signup by Sunday, May 30th to qualify. Go to the following link and submit your form today. When it asks for student number, enter a “0”. If you have any questions please contact Mrs. Knight gknight@woodall.k12.ok.us or Mrs Kocsis kkocsis@woodalk.k12.ok.us

post_text: Spots are filling up fast!! Transfers to our district will be accepted. It is that time of year to enroll our NEW PreK and NEW kindergarten students. NEW Kindergarten enrollment is for students who do not currently attend PreK at Woodall. We are going to have to enroll a little differently this year. Our online enrollment is in the process of being developed. Until then, you will enroll your child by emailing Mrs Knight at (gknight@woodall.k12.ok.us) the following information: parent name, address, phone number, child’s name, and child’s birthday. Your child will be placed on our list which will reserve their place in one of our classes. When our online enrollment is ready, we will contact you to complete the process. At that time you will need your child’s birth certificate, social security card, CDIB card, blue tribal membership card, shot record, and proof of residency. We are excited for our new Woodall Wildcats!

shared_text:
Woodall STEAM
April 7 at 8:38 PM ·

Congratulations to Kaylie Richardson, 1st place winner in the Social & Behavioral Science Category at the 2020 Oklahoma State Science and Engineering Fair! 🏆 👏🏼 She is also a Broadcom MASTER Winner.

Congratulations to McKenna Hood for winning the prestigious Lemelson Early Inventor Prize for the development of an outstanding invention! This award comes with a $100 cash prize. 💵 🏅

This would have been both girls’ second appearance at OSSEF, but due to COVID-19, the fair went virtual this year with all documents being submitted online and judging solely based on paperwork. While these are heartbreaking times for all, it’s moments like these we praise and relish in!

shared_text:
Ginger Knight is with Tiara Fourkiller and 28 others.
April 3 at 6:46 PM ·

Woodall Staff,
I wanted to take a minute to thank all of you for what you are doing for our kids. I know this has not been easy. You were asked to reimagine what school for our students looked like, over night. But, you all stepped up and handled the situation like the professionals you are. I appreciate the extra time the teachers have all invested this last week, preparing lessons and materials. I appreciate how easy it was to come up with a continuous learning plan because we knew, we were working with the best school staff in Oklahoma to implement the plan. I am thankful for Rachelle, Kim, Donna, Tina, Carol, Deb, and Guillermo who are keeping our kids fed, daily. I am so proud to be a Woodall Wildcat! We are Woodall! Some wish for it....WE work for it! Thank you!

I wanted to take a minute to thank all of you for what you are doing for our kids. I know this has not been easy. You were asked to reimagine what school for our students looked like, over night. But, you all stepped up and handled the situation like the professionals you are. I appreciate the extra time the teachers have all invested this last week, preparing lessons and materials. I appreciate how easy it was to come up with a continuous learning plan because we knew, we were working with the best school staff in Oklahoma to implement the plan. I am thankful for Rachelle, Kim, Donna, Tina, Carol, Deb, and Guillermo who are keeping our kids fed, daily. I am so proud to be a Woodall Wildcat! We are Woodall! Some wish for it....WE work for it! Thank you!

post_text:
Good evening, everybody:

What a beautiful sunset this evening...I hope you had a chance to catch a glimpse. The simple things are still the BEST!

With the action taken by the State Board of Education today, we now have a directive. The leadership team along with teachers and staff will work virtually next week to develop our plan for continual learning for all Woodall students through May 8th.

We look forward to unveiling our plan and are excited to get back to the business of educating students. The delivery method may look different but I can assure you it will be good!

Please be watching for a survey about the technology you have available in your home. The information you provide will prove valuable as we gather resources to make available for students.

We miss all of you and are making ready to get connected again. Please take extra care and precautions to keep well.

L. Clinkenbeard

If you filled out the meal survey for delivery, look for our school bus between 9:00-11:00 each day. Please come to the bus to receive the meals. If you chose pick-up, please drive through our student pick-up line between 9:00-11:00. No need to get out of car, we will hand meals through car window. I will be in the office on Monday, March 23rd between 8:00-1:00. If you did not fill out a survey for meals, call the office 918-456-1581 and I will add you to our list. If you need to pick-up your child’s medication, please do so during this time. After Monday, our school and offices will be closed until April 6th, except for meal prep and delivery. Everyone take care!

post_text: Something for our older Woodall students. Thanks Mrs Fourkiller.
shared_text:
Tiara Fourkiller
March 18 at 4:11 PM ·

Notes from a Social Studies teacher:

Parents, I don’t have pre-teens or teenagers in my house yet but I’ve seen a few of my friends post and all I can say is... may the odds be ever in your favor. 🤪 BUT I came up with an idea for students that I think would be a fun and educational thing for them to do.

For my 6th-8th classes we have talked about what a primary source is. Right now your kids are living through history. A history lesson that they will probably take in the next few years and even beyond that will talk about with their kids one day. They are a primary source, a first hand account of whats happening. I’ve attached a possible *lesson* or fun activity that you all can do together. Tell them to save them! It will come in handy some day. Enjoy and please share what they come up with to satisfy my nerdy teacher heart. ❤️

Woodall STEAM is at Booker T. Washington High School (Tulsa, Oklahoma).
November 16, 2019 at 8:58 PM · Tulsa, OK ·

Woodall Wildcats came and conquered! The kiddos competed today against 24 other teams in Oklahoma’s largest FIRST LEGO League Single Qualifier. Kool Kats Team #46747 won 2nd place in the Core Values category and Luna Squad Team #46748 are 1st place champions and are advancing to State on December 14 at Tulsa Memorial High School! There are simply no words to express how proud I am of these students - they faced several, unexpected obstacles today and worked together to solve them and come out on top 🧡🖤

Thank you, Mrs. Lajuana Corbell, for volunteering to drive us and for making today all the more special!

📚 BOOK FAIR VOLUNTEERS 📚

Ms. Hudgens (our Librarian) is needing volunteers for the Book Fair.
Dates & Times: September 23 - 27 from 7:30am - 3:30pm.
If you can help out for just a couple hours or the entire day it will be appreciated! The mornings are always the busiest from 7:30-8:30, so volunteers for that hour would be amazing!

They also dissected squid!

Woodall 4H Club
March 10, 2019 at 12:09 PM ·

This past week Erica Ward, Macy McCrary, Jolee Taylor, Madison Troyer, Maci Childress, Emmy Foreman, Colt Ward, & Remington Cooper exhibited their animals at the Muskogee Regional Junior Livestock Show.

Special congratulations goes to Maci Childress for winning 1st in her class with her Cross Pig. She also made the Premium Sale with her cross.

Over 900 4H and FFA members from 8 different counties showed at the Regional Show. Those 900 kids exhibited over 1,500 animals (pigs, goats, sheep, & cattle). Of those 900+ exhibitors, only 166 made the Premium Sale.

Congratulations Woodall students & Woodall 4H Members. Mrs. Cooper is proud of you!!!

post_text:
With the next state legislative session just around the corner, it is anticipated that the issue of school consolidation in one form or another is expected to once again be a hot topic at the Capitol. Recognizing this, KOTV is doing a news segment on this topic to air next Thursday. Dave Davis, reporter for Channel 6, spent some time on campus last month learning about Woodall and K8 schools in general. My understanding is that the segment will also include interview(s)with proponents for school consolidation.
From an educator’s perspective, the true and foremost issue for the legislature with regards to schools should be finding sustainable adequate funding for all public schools and ensuring that all school entities that receive state funding are held accountable in the same manner. As the legislative season gets underway next month I’ll make posts on actions that pertain to education to keep you as informed as possible.

post_text: Thanks to all who gave of their time to participate in our Native American Heritage Assembly today. A special thank you to members of Woodall’s Indian Education Committee for their roles in the planning process to make this assembly our best yet! Wildcats of all ages listened intently to the creation story about the opossum and his once beautiful tail and audience members were just as attentive as the regalia from different tribes was described in detailed and then personally modeled. Current students along with Woodall alumni and parents were among the ones dressed in regalia. All in attendance thoroughly enjoyed the Powwow drummers and dancers and there was no hesitation from our students when they were invited to join the dancers on the floor!

shared_text:
Woodall Wildcats - Athletics
November 8, 2018 at 11:11 PM ·

5/6th grade girls lost their opener 24-12 but played hard and never quit.

5/6th boys won big 26-7 they got after it and played really tough.

Varsity Girls picked up right where they left off from last year. They look to be extremely athletic and will have key pieces coming of the bench that will help them continue to get up and down the court. They won it going away 47-4!!! They also broke out some new threads for tonight’s game!!!

The football boys were still in football form and haven’t quite made the transition to basketball with only practicing a couple days. It was not pretty at all but came away with the win. They play hard and you won’t lacking for entertainment 😀!!! They came away with the 49-27 win. Good night of basketball for the Wildcat Nation.

I also understand that the 3/4th grade boys were the winners of our tournament.
Congratulations Fellas!!!

Woodall Orange places 3rd in the girls bracket!! Way to play ladies!!!

#wildcatpride

post_text: Friday morning, November 9 at 9:30 in the Event Center, Woodall will remember Eugene Woodrow Wicker, a sailor on the USS Oklahoma on December 7, 1941 at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii. Although, he died that day, he has just recently been laid to rest at Fort Gibson National Cemetery. Mr. Wicker's nephew will be our guest speaker to share more about his uncle. The public is invited to attend this very special Veteran's Day Assembly.
